# IoC Container (Dependency Injection)

The IoC (Inversion of Control) Container is a global registry of [bold]services[/bold] — managers, systems, and utilities that your code needs.

Instead of creating instances directly, you ask the IoC container for them. This decouples your code and makes testing easier.

## The Core Concept

### What is Dependency Injection?

Instead of this (bad):

public class CombatSystem
{
    private HealthSystem _healthSystem = new HealthSystem();  // Creates it

    public void AttackEnemy(EntityUid enemy)
    {
        _healthSystem.ApplyDamage(enemy, 10);  // Uses it
    }
}


Do this (good):

public class CombatSystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly HealthSystem _healthSystem = default!;  // Injected

    public void AttackEnemy(EntityUid enemy)
    {
        _healthSystem.ApplyDamage(enemy, 10);  // Uses it
    }
}


The [bold]difference:[/bold]
- Bad version: CombatSystem creates its own HealthSystem
- Good version: IoC provides HealthSystem to CombatSystem

### Benefits:
- [bold]Loose coupling[/bold] — CombatSystem doesn't know how HealthSystem is created
- [bold]Easy testing[/bold] — inject a mock HealthSystem in tests
- [bold]Single responsibility[/bold] — HealthSystem has one source of truth
- [bold]Flexibility[/bold] — swap implementations without changing CombatSystem

## How to Use IoCManager

### Getting a Service


// Most common pattern - using Dependency attribute
public class MySystem : EntitySystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IEntityManager _entityManager = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly TransformSystem _transformSystem = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly ChatSystem _chatSystem = default!;
}


The Dependency attribute tells IoC to inject these services when MySystem is created.

### Manual Resolution (Less Common)


var entityManager = IoCManager.Resolve();
var chatSystem = IoCManager.Resolve();


Use this only when you can't use the Dependency attribute (rare cases).

## Common Services in OpenEdge 14

[bold]Engine services:[/bold]
- [mono]IEntityManager[/mono] — Create, query, and modify entities
- [mono]IActionBlockerSystem[/mono] — Determine if actions are allowed
- [mono]IConfigurationManager[/mono] — Access config values
- [mono]ILogManager[/mono] — Log messages to console
- [mono]IMapManager[/mono] — Manage maps and grids
- [mono]IRobustRandom[/mono] — Random number generation
- [mono]TransformSystem[/mono] — Handle entity positions
- [mono]PhysicsSystem[/mono] — Handle collisions and forces
- [mono]AudioSystem[/mono] — Play sounds
- [mono]AnimationSystem[/mono] — Play animations

[bold]OpenEdge-Specific services:[/bold]
- [mono]OE14CharacterStatsSystem[/mono] — Process character stats and modifiers
- [mono]OE14SkillSystem[/mono] — Manage skill trees and progression
- [mono]OE14MagicEnergySystem[/mono] — Handle mana pools and regeneration
- [mono]OE14CombatSystem[/mono] — Process attacks and damage
- [mono]OE14EconomySystem[/mono] — Manage currency and trading
- [mono]OE14CookingSystem[/mono] — Handle food preparation

## Accessing Services in Code

### In a System (Recommended)


public sealed class MyCustomSystem : EntitySystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IEntityManager _entityManager = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly OE14CharacterStatsSystem _statsSystem = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly ChatSystem _chatSystem = default!;

    public override void Update(float frameTime)
    {
        // Use injected services
        var entities = _entityManager.GetEntities();
        var stats = _statsSystem.GetStats(someEntity);
        _chatSystem.SendMessage("Hello world");
    }
}


### In an Event Handler


public sealed partial class DamageEventHandler
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IEntityManager _entityManager = default!;

    private void OnDamage(DamageEvent args)
    {
        // Use service
        var health = _entityManager.GetComponent(args.Target);
        health.Health -= args.Amount;
    }
}


### In a Component (Entity System Framework)


public sealed partial class OE14CharacterStatsComponent : Component
{
    // Components usually don't use [Dependency]
    // Instead, they store data and systems process them
}


[bold]Note:[/bold] Components are data, not behavior. Don't use the Dependency attribute in components.

## Registering Custom Services

When you create a new system, it needs to be registered in IoC so others can access it.


// In a startup class or initialization code:
IoCManager.Register();


The framework usually handles this automatically for most systems.

## Service Lifetime

Services in IoC have different lifetimes:

### Singleton (Default)

IoCManager.Register(new ConfigurationManager());

- Created once
- Persists for entire game runtime
- Thread-safe

### Per-Resolve (Creates New Each Time)

IoCManager.Register(() => new MyFactory());

- Created fresh each time you resolve
- Rarely used

Most services are singletons.

## Dependency Chains

Services can depend on other services:


CombatSystem needs:
  |
HealthSystem, PhysicsSystem, AudioSystem

PhysicsSystem needs:
  |
TransformSystem, IMapManager

TransformSystem needs:
  |
IEntityManager

All automatically resolved!


When you inject CombatSystem, IoC automatically ensures all its dependencies exist.

## Real Example: Character Stats


public sealed class OE14CharacterStatsSystem : EntitySystem
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IEntityManager _entityManager = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly IActionBlockerSystem _actionBlocker = default!;

    public override void Update(float frameTime)
    {
        // Get all entities with character stats
        var query = EntityQueryEnumerator();
        while (query.MoveNext(out var uid, out var stats))
        {
            // Calculate effective stats
            stats.EffectiveStats = CalculateEffectiveStats(stats.BaseStats, stats.Modifiers);

            // Check if any stat is capped
            foreach (var stat in stats.EffectiveStats)
            {
                if (stat.Value >= MaxStatValue)
                {
                    // Notify action blocker of limitations
                    _actionBlocker.BlockAction(uid, ActionType.SpellCast);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    private Dictionary CalculateEffectiveStats(...)
    {
        // Complex calculation
    }
}


Both [mono]_entityManager[/mono] and [mono]_actionBlocker[/mono] are provided by IoC.

## Pitfalls to Avoid

[bold]Don't Resolve in Constructor:[/bold]

// Bad!
public MySystem()
{
    var service = IoCManager.Resolve();  // Don't do this
}


[bold]Do Use the Dependency Attribute:[/bold]

// Good!
[Dependency] private readonly SomeService _service = default!;


[bold]Don't Access IoCManager Repeatedly:[/bold]

// Bad!
public void DoSomething()
{
    var service1 = IoCManager.Resolve();
    var service2 = IoCManager.Resolve();
}


[bold]Do Inject Once:[/bold]

[Dependency] private readonly ServiceA _serviceA = default!;
[Dependency] private readonly ServiceB _serviceB = default!;


## Testing with IoC

The strength of IoC shines in testing:


[Test]
public void TestCombatDamage()
{
    // Create mock services
    var mockEntityManager = new MockEntityManager();
    var mockHealthSystem = new MockHealthSystem();

    // Register mocks
    IoCManager.Register(mockEntityManager);
    IoCManager.Register(mockHealthSystem);

    // Test your system
    var combatSystem = new CombatSystem();
    combatSystem.Attack(enemy, 10);

    // Verify
    Assert.That(mockHealthSystem.ApplyDamageCalls, Is.EqualTo(1));
}


Much easier than testing tightly-coupled code!

## Service Discovery

To find what services are available, search the codebase:


# Find all registered services
grep -r "IoCManager.Register<" Content.Server/_OE14/

# Find a specific interface
grep -r "interface IMyService" Content.Shared/_OE14/


Or consult the [textlink="System Reference" link="OE14_DEV_SystemReference"] section of this guidebook.

## Navigation

- Want to use a service in code? Use the Dependency attribute
- Need to create a new system? Inherit from [mono]EntitySystem[/mono] and it auto-registers
- Testing your code? Use mocks with IoC for easy substitution
- Looking for a specific service? Check [textlink="System Reference" link="OE14_DEV_SystemReference"]

## Summary

- [bold]Services[/bold] are managers and systems available globally
- [bold]Dependency Injection[/bold] decouples your code
- [bold]Dependency attribute[/bold] injects services automatically
- [bold]IoCManager.Resolve\()[/bold] gets services manually (rare)
- [bold]Testing[/bold] becomes easy with mock services

Use IoC everywhere in OpenEdge 14!
